We recommended and the Municipal Mayor and the Sangguniang Bayan agreed to exhaust all possible remedies to demand the liquidation or refund of the unliquidated cash advances from the accountable officers.

We further recommended the following:

For the concerned municipal officials and employees to settle immediately their unliquidated cash advances;

Withhold the salaries and other emoluments in full of officials and employees who are still in service effective immediately and apply the said withheld amounts in their respective outstanding cash advances;

The Municipal Accountant:

to adequately and properly prepare the Report of Unliquidated Cash Advances;

to secure original copy of Disbursement Vouchers, photocopy copy of Check issued, Obligation Request/ Certification of Appropriations, Funds and Obligation of Allotment and other supporting documents relating to the granting of cash advance for proper reference in the event of administrative or judicial demand to settle the unliquidated cash advances of accountable officer/s; and

to exert earnest effort to locate the documents relating to prior years’ cash advances with “no data available” remarks.

The OIC-Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant to ensure that no cash advance remain unliquidated at year-end pursuant to COA Circular No. 97-002.

For the Management to have an assurance that inventories are safeguarded against risk of misapplication or misuse, we recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to direct Municipal Accountant and the Supply Officer the following:

To record inventory using the prescribed perpetual method of accounting and strictly adhere to the pro-forma accounting entries on all purchased supplies and materials;

To maintain perpetual Supplies Ledger Cards and Stock Cards for each type of supplies and materials;

To conduct regular reconciliation of the ledger and the stock cards to ensure that all purchases and issuances are properly accounted for;

Require the Inventory Committee to conduct a comprehensive physical count of all types of inventory items semestrally, prepare the RPCI and submit the same to the Auditor concerned not later than July 31 and January 31 of each year for the first and second semesters, respectively. Also, invite representative from the COA to act as witness in the physical count; and

To ensure the reliability and accuracy of the accounts presented in the financial statements.

We recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to instruct the following:

Inventory Committee to prioritize the conduct of a thorough and complete physical count of all properties at least once a year and subsequently prepare the RPCPPE using the proper format and to submit a copy of the said reports to the Audit Team not later than January 31 of every year;

Designated Property Officer to maintain Property Cards for all the PPEs of the LGU;

Municipal Accountant to maintain  Property Ledger Cards and be reconciled with the Property Cards of the Property Officer-Designate;

Designated Property Officer, the Inventory Committee, and the Municipal Accountant to adhere to the guidelines and procedures set forth under COA Circular 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020, to reflect a more reliable balances of PPE accounts.

We recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to instruct the Municipal Accountant to:

Conduct analysis and review the cause of discrepancy by tracing and locating the documents affecting the reciprocal accounts;

Prepare the necessary adjusting entries in the books of accounts through the preparation of Journal Entry Voucher (JEV) duly supported with documents, explanations and/or computations in order to reflect the correct balances of accounts in the financial statements;

Maintain subsidiary ledger and conduct regular reconciliation of the accounts to ensure that the balances of reciprocal accounts are the same at all times.

We recommended and Municipal Mayor agreed to direct the Municipal Accountant to:

Coordinate with the Municipal Disaster Risk and Reduction Management Officer to determine the final amount of unexpended balance to be transferred to the Special Trust Fund;

Ensure timely recording and recognition of the transfer of the unexpended balance of the QRF and the DRRMF-MOOE of DRMMF to the Special Trust Fund under the account "Trust Liability-DRRM" in the Trust Fund Books at year-end, in accordance with Item 5.1.10 of COA Circular No. 2012-002;

Provide the details of the unexpended balance of LDRRMF as supplementary disclosures in the Note to Financial Statements, as required by Item 5.1.16 of COA Circular 2012-002; and

Transfer of the remaining balance of the unspent LDRRMF amounting to ₱16,064.56 in the Trust Liability – DRRMF account under the Trust Fund.

