We recommended and the LCE agreed to direct the:

a. Municipal Treasurer and the Market Administrator to: 

i.	issue the necessary follow up/ demand letters to the accountable delinquent tenants for the settlement of delinquent accounts; 

ii.	initiate legal action, if warranted, to collect the long overdue arrearages;


iii.	require the tenants to execute valid contracts, and observe faithful compliance of the duties and obligations, and penalize them in case of any breach or violation stipulated thereto;

iv.	submit an updated master list of tenants and reconcile the same with the actual occupants and numbers of market stalls appearing in the structure layout plan of the two markets to clearly establish that all units are properly accounted, recorded and included in the monthly report of market collections and prevent the sub-leasing of the stalls; and

v.	resolve the issues on occupation of area of 111 tenants who have no valid contracts with the Municipality;

b. Municipal Accountant to:

i.	maintain the Special Accounts for market operations in the General Fund and recognize in the books the accrued receivables for rental fees of ₱1,162,320.00; and 

ii.	prepare the corresponding schedules to support the financial statements which will serve as tools in informing management for evaluation and decision-making purposes.

We recommended and the LCE agreed to instruct the GFPS to:

a. continue its efforts to improve gender mainstreaming to achieve full compliance with the provisions of relevant laws and regulations; 

b. improve the reporting functions and ensure that GAD internal data are consistent and corroborative in order to be useful to the users; 

c. inform the concerned DILG in writing of any update and changes in the GPB; and


d. direct all members of the GFPS to conduct a gender analysis of the Municipality’s PPA’S through the administration of HGDG for purposes of GAD budget attribution.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to (a) ensure the strict adherence to the provisions of COA Circular No. 2012-001 and Section 4 (6) of PD No. 1445 regarding complete documentation of claims against government funds; 

(b) direct the Municipal accountant to review the completeness and validity of the supporting documents of the claim before certifying the Disbursement Vouchers and allowing its payment;

 and (c) require the concerned Municipal Officials to submit the necessary supporting documents to prove the regularity of the claim.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the Municipal Treasurer to develop strategies that would intensify the collections of RPT which includes (a) conduct of frequent tax campaigns; 

(b) preparation of Notice of Delinquency; and 

(c) submission of Certificates of RPT Delinquency on all delinquent RPT accounts to the Sanggunian to request for assistance in the enforcement of remedial measures provided in Sections 256 to 258 of RA 7160.

We have recommended that:

Accountable Officers strictly remit their daily collections to Municipal Treasurer as required under Section 29 of the Manual of NGAS, Volume I; 

Management institute mechanism or policy that there will be no new set /pads of accountable forms to be issued unless previously issued are already used-up and corresponding amount collected are reported and remitted. Therefore, part of this policy should include among others a reconciliation of the RCD of the AOS with the log book where issuances for Accountable Forms (AFs) are recorded;

A certification by the AOs that all AFs issued to them are already used and the amount of collections remitted;

Enhance if there exist the set internal control measures of the LGU on the area of monitoring Accountable Forms issuances and its corresponding collection remittances;

Management instill in the minds of the AOs that it will institute disciplinary actions against them if warranted that they have deliberately delayed revenue collection remittances.

